FLORA OF LA GARCIA WILDERNESS
COLORADO, USA
Rosaceae
Potentilla subjuga Rydb.
Det: Suez Janssen, 31 July 2018
SAGUACHE COUNTY: Northwest ridge of Organ Mountains, La
Guarita Wilderness Area, Gunnison National Forest. Ca. 39.6084,
-104.9711, WGS84. Ca. 3787 m elevation. Fellfield; west-facing
slope. Extremely dry. Soils: Rocks outcrops; volcanic breccia. Terrain:
Mountains ridge. With Sedum lanceolatum; Carex elynoides.
Leaves area dark green adaxial and white abaxial. Abundance:
Frequent. Flowers. Tissue Sample collected.
2 July 2018 Suez Janssen 113
Kathryn Kalmbach Herbarium (KHD), Denver Botanic Gardens

UNIVERSITY OF MINNESOTA
MINNEAPOLIS
Betula x sandbergii Britt.
(probably backcross to B. pumila var. glands.)
Minnesota, Anoka Co.: Ca. 5 miles F of Cedar in
Sect. 26, T32N, R23Wind bog just Nof Co. Road 22,
Shrub ca. & ft. tall with 5 main stems 1" DBR;
Bark reddish-brown, tight. Open fairly west part
of bog; soil mucky. Rare. Associated with
Betula papyrifera, B. pumila var. glandulifera,
Populus tremuloides, few Cornus stolonifera, many
Seitz.
Coll. K. E. Clausen 304 Date 6-8-1958

column3:
Herbarium of Rancho Santa Ana Botanic Garden Plants of Kern Co., California, USA RANUNCULACEAE Delphinium hansenii (Greene) Greene ssp. kernense (A. Davidse.) Ewan Sierra Nevada; Southern Sierra Nevada region: Piute Mountains, lower Esperanza Canyon at eastern base of Sorrell Peak and western edge of Kelso Valley. 350 25.121'N, 118" 15.378'W. Alto.: 1372-1463m/4500-4800ft. Alluvial flats and moderate to steep slopes. granitic substrate with large boulders outcrops, loose,. decomposed granite soils. Vegetation recently burned (2006 or 2007), formerly dominated by scrub of Artemisia tridentata, Chrysothamnus nauseosus, Yucca brevifolia on flats, drier slopes, scrubby woodland of Pinus sabiniana, Pinus monophylla, Quercus wislizeni, Quercus chrysolepis, Fremontodendron californicum, Ribes spp., Cercocarpus betuloides, Ceanothus vestitus, Rhamnus californica on steeper slopes and more mesic exposures. Rich and diverse display of annuals and perennial herbs On burned area and in adjacent areas of unburned vegetation. Coarse perennial herb, flowers dark purple tipped with white. Occasional. Steven Boyd 11968 1 May 2008
w/ Valentine Arvizu Entered into ROSA Database ((16134ROSA)

- "eventDate" which is the year the specimen was collected
- "recordedBy" which is the person who collected the specimen
- "institutionCode" which is the institution where the herbarium sample is kept.

The herbarium label text provides a lot of interesting botanical information which can be placed into a JSON format using DarwinCore fields.

Here is a possible representation:

```JSON
{
  "institutionCode": "Tule University of Texas Herbarium, West Texas State University",
  "country": "USA",
  "stateProvince": "New Mexico",
  "county": "Roosevelt County",

  "scientificName": "Croton dioicus Cave",
  "recordedBy": "Larry C. Higgins",
  "recordNumber": "8665",
  "eventDate": "1974-06-13",
  "basisOfRecord": "Herbarium"
}
```
In the JSON above, some of the DarwinCore fields used are:
- `institutionCode`: the institution(s) where the specimen was kept.
- `country`, `stateProvince`, `county`: the details of the geography where the specimen was found.
- `locality`: specifics of the habitat.
- `dynamicProperties`: any interesting properties of the habitat.
- `scientificName`: the scientific name of the specimen.
- `recordedBy`: the person who recorded the specimen.
- `recordNumber`: an ID for the specimen record.
- `eventDate`: the date the specimen was recorded.
- `basisOfRecord`: describes the type of the specimen record.

column3:
eU.S.A.
Rosaceae Prunus serotina Ehrh.
det. M. Nees, 2014
MISSOURI, Lewis Co., Wakonda State Park, just Nof
Boulder Lake campground, along ledges of Boulder Lake.
40°00°37°N, 91°30°54"W. alt. 148 m.
Very flat terrace, floodplain of Mississippi River, the Park
on old ponds and mounds from alluvial gravel extraction
decades lago, completely surrounded by crop fields. thin
young woods of Ulmus americana, Populus deltoides,
Cornus drummondii, Toxicodendron radicans, Morus alba,
on disturbed gravel. much calcareous.
Tree 9 m. tall, 20 cm. in diameter; bark dark and flaky.
Flowers fragrant (sunny afternoon at dusky); petals white.
Coll.: M. Nees 61019 11 May 2014
MISSOURI BOTANICAL GARDEN (MO)

column3:

PLANTS OF THE CALIFORNIA ISLANDS
Fabaceae
Lupinus concinnus J. Agardh
Wings pale blue, banner white, keels whitish with rosea
tip. Santa Barbara County: Santa Cruz Island. On E side
of Alamos Canyon, just NWof creek crossing of
Horqueta Road. Locally common; W-facing slope; ISCI
Schist. Elevation: 400 feet.
Associated species: Baccharis pilularis, Opuntia
littoralis, Heterotheca grandiflora, Gnaphalium
canescens microcephalum, Plantago erecta,
Hypochaeris glabra, Lotus hamatus, Erodium botrys,
Silene gallica, Cardionema ramosissimum, Selaginella
bigelovii, Vulpia myuros, Avena fatua, Lamarckia
aurea.
Stevens A. Juana SC-3842 12 Apr 1994
SANTA BARBARA BOTANICO GARDEN (QSBG)

column3:
ASTERACEAE OF UTAH
Cirsium cf. calcareum (ME Jones) Wooton
and Standley X C. rydbergii Petrak
SAN JUAN COUNTY. Ca 2/3 miles up Sweet
Alice Canyon from its entrance and jeep
trail, ca 3/4 miles west of Ruins Canyon,
in Beef Basin, northeast of Dark
Canyon, in vicinity of 37d 56’ N flat,
109d 54’ 48" W along, 1890 meters.
In open wash in cryptogamic soil, with
Pinus edulis, Artemesia tridentata,
Frasera speciosa, Populus fremontii,
Senecio, Salix exigua, S bonplandiana,
Rosa woodsii, Chrysothamnus, Berberis
fremontii, Echinocereus
triglochidiatus, Opuntia spp,
Sclerocactus parviflorus, Rhus
trilobata, Amelanchier, Fraxinus
anomalus, Juniperus, Chrysopsis
villosa, Gilia roseata, Cirsium cf.
calcareum, C rydbergii, Lepidium,
Clematis ligusticifolia, Hymenoxys,
Oenothera longissima, Forestiera,
Linum, Castilleja linearifolia,
Phragmites, Solidago. Uncommon and
local as farm as cana tell, not in
flowers.
7 July 1994
Denise Buchanan
Wendy Hodgson 8434
Herbarium of Desert Botanical Garden
(DESC)

column3:
HERBARIUM OF CALIFORNIA STATE UNIVERSITY, CHICO
Silene occidentalis S. Watson ssp. occidentalis
Plumas County, CALIFORNIA Elevation 1707 m
T23N, R8E, NE%/ of SE% of sec. 23 Lat: N 39' 50' 22"
Dogwood Peak quad Long: W 121° 02' 45"
Northern High Sierra Nevada. Top of south-facing slope overlook-
wing Middle Fork Feather River; head of Sherman Creek. Wildfire
killed mixed conifer forest (Ponderosa pine, white fir, black oak,
incense cedar; Arctostaphylos patula, Garrya fremontii, Prunus
emarginata, Ceanothus cordulatus; Monardella odoratissima ssp.
pallida, Helianthella californica var. nevadensis, Nama lobbii,
Symphoricarpos mollis, Wyethia mollis, Eriogonum nudum, Carex
brainerdii. Stems strictly erecta; flowers greenish-yellow; plants
very sticky.
L. P. Janeway 7259 3/VII/2001

column3:
ROSACEAE OF UTAH
Fragaria virginiana Duchesne
var. glauca Watson
SAN JUAN COUNTY. Manti-La Salt National Forest,
Peavine Canyon, Trail No. 157, within 1/2 to 4-1/2 miles
below trailhead towards junction of Kigalia Canyon, just
south of Dark Canyon, between 37 3930 and 37°
4315 N, 109° 51’ and 109 52 30 W, 7280-7760 feet,
2218-2360 meters.
With Pinus ponderosa, Populus tremuloides, Lupinus
argenteus palmeri, Abies, Taraxacum, Senecio
integerrimus, Prunus virginiana, Achillea millefolium,
Phlox longifolia, Mertensia franciscana, Smilacina
stellata, Ribes cereum, Pseudotsuga menziesii,
Penstemon lentus albiflorus, Potentilla gracilis,
Juniperus communis, Clematis columbiana, Aquilegia
caerulea, Viola, Phlox hoodii, Arctostaphylos patula,
Erigeron kachinensis, Geranium caespitosum,
Hymenoxys argentea, Cirsium, Quercus gambelii,
Symphoricarpos oreophilus, Lathyrus. Locally common
in open, rhizomatous herbaceous perennial, flowers
white.
23 June 1995
Wendy Hodgson 9432
with Roan Hill
Herbarium of Desert Botanical Garden (DESC)

column3:
1O
University of Florida Herbarium (#LAS) Gainesville, FL U.S.A. Plants of Texas
Cactaceae’
Opuntia fusco-atra Engelm.
Fayette Co., Off of Interstate 10W, ca. 2 Wolf
Schulenberg, sandy prairie; assoc. w/ Mimosa, Sorghum
halapense, Cnidosculus texanus, Celtis laevigata,
Juniperus virginiana, Liatris, Andropogon, Solanum,
abundant locally; plants spreading, only slightly
ascending, spines to 2/areoles, spreading away from none
another, white towards the tips, dark brown-castaneous at
the base, glochids red-reddish brown, tepals yellow,
basally tinged red, 2n=44. note: this taxon is mostly placed
in O. macrorhiza. 29.69123°N 96.98311°W.
Lucas C. Majure 3505 5 Aug 2008
With Terrence C. Majure
